It is remarkable that the maximum density in the system only decreases in time (except for possible minor fluctuations) during the black hole–neutron star binary coalescences. This is a striking difference from the binary-neutron-star merger, after which a massive or collapsing neutron star with increased central density is formed (see, e.g., Hotokezaka et al. 2011; Takami et al. 2015; Dietrich et al. 2015; Foucart et al. 2016a). This property indicates that black hole–neutron star binaries are not influenced by the equation of state at very high density, e.g., several times the nuclear saturation density, unless the neutron star is close to the maximum-mass configuration. Thus, numerical simulations for binaries with plausibly canonical ∼1.4M⊙\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
