The final fate of the black hole-neutron star binaries is classified into two categories. One is tidal disruption of the neutron star before the plunge, and the other is the plunge of the neutron star into the black hole before tidal disruption. Tidal disruption is a more likely outcome for systems with a lower mass ratio, a higher prograde spin of the black hole, and/or a smaller compactness of the neutron star. If the black hole is nonspinning, tidal disruption of a neutron star with ∼1.35M⊙\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
