One of the lessons from the LIGO-Virgo O3 is that realistic compact object binaries sometimes challenge our ability to distinguish black holes and neutron stars (Abbott et al. 2020a, c). Because the sensitivity of the current detectors are not high enough, some parameters of gravitational-wave sources such as the masses of individual objects are not determined precisely. Moreover, because we do not know the precise upper limit of the neutron-star mass, an object with ≈2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
